n-section-title">Learn</div><div class="dropdown-links"><a href="/blog/" class="dropdown-link">All Articles</a><a href="/blog/ozempic-india-guide" class="dropdown-link">Ozempic Guide</a><a href="/blog/pcos-symptoms-india" class="dropdown-link">PCOS Guide</a><a href="/blog/hba1c-test-guide" class="dropdown-link">HbA1c Test</a><a href="/blog/finasteride-india-guide" class="dropdown-link">Finasteride Guide</a><a href="/blog/tretinoin-indian-skin-guide" class="dropdown-link">Tretinoin Guide</a><a href="/blog/hrv-explained" class="dropdown-link">HRV Explained</a></div></div><div class="dropdown-section"><a href="#" class="dropdown-cta" onclick="event.preventDefault();closeDropdown();openWaitlist();">Join the waitlist. <i class="ph-bold ph-arrow-right"></i></a></div></div><!-- ═══ ARTICLE HERO ═══ --><section class="article-hero"><div class="article-content"><span class="article-eyebrow">Skin care guide</span><h1 class="article-h1">How to Get a Tretinoin Prescription in India. <em>(Without the Waiting Room)</em></h1><div class="article-meta"><div class="article-meta-item"><i class="ph-fill ph-calendar"></i><span>April 16, 2026</span></div><div class="article-meta-item"><i class="ph-fill ph-user-circle"></i><span>arq. medical team</span></div><div class="article-meta-badge"><i class="ph-fill ph-stethoscope"></i>
 Medically reviewed
 </div></div></div></section><!-- ═══ ARTICLE BODY ═══ --><section class="article-body"><p><strong>Tretinoin is the gold standard for acne and anti-aging.</strong> It's also Schedule H in India — prescription-only. That means you can't just walk into a pharmacy and buy it. But the barrier to access has dropped dramatically with telehealth. A 10-minute video consult with a physician, brief. <a href="/skin" style="color:var(--gold);text-decoration:underline;text-decoration-color:rgba(184,146,46,0.3);transition:all .2s">skin</a> assessment, and prescription delivered to your pharmacy — no waiting room, no unnecessary appointments. Here's exactly how to get prescribed and use tretinoin safely, especially on Indian skin where the stakes are higher.</p><!-- TL;DR --><div class="tldr-box"><span class="box-eyebrow">Key takeaways</span><h3>Getting tretinoin in India</h3><ul><li><strong>Legal status</strong> Schedule H drug (prescription-only). Buying OTC from pharmacies without prescription is technically illegal.</li><li><strong>Online prescription</strong> Telehealth physician consult → skin assessment → prescription issued legally</li><li><strong>Starting concentration</strong> 0.025% for beginners (lowest, least irritating)</li><li><strong>Why physician oversight matters</strong> Purging management, post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) prevention in darker skin, proper sunscreen protocol</li><li><strong>Indian brands</strong> Retino-A (retinoic acid), Tretin, A-Ret (all , 20g)</li><li><strong>Timeline</strong> Results in 12+ weeks for acne; 16+ weeks for fine lines</li></ul></div><h2>Is Tretinoin Legal in India? And How Do You Get It?</h2><p>Yes, tretinoin is legal in India. It's a Schedule H drug, which means</p><ul><li><strong>Schedule H = Prescription-only.</strong> A registered medical practitioner (MBBS, MD, dermatologist) must prescribe it.</li><li><strong>You cannot legally buy it OTC.</strong> Many pharmacies sell it without asking for a prescription, but this bypasses medical oversight.</li><li><strong>Prescription is mandatory.</strong> This is good — it ensures proper dosing and safety monitoring, especially for skin like yours (melanin-rich skin has specific PIH risks).</li></ul><p><strong>How to get prescribed</strong></p><p><strong>1. Telehealth Consult (arq. or similar)</strong><br/>
Schedule a video consult with a licensed physician. Describe your skin concerns (acne, texture, anti-aging). Show photos if relevant. Takes 10 minutes.</p><p><strong>2. Skin Assessment</strong><br/>
Physician assesses skin type, Fitzpatrick scale (important for PIH risk), current skin routine, sensitivities. This info determines starting concentration.</p><p><strong>3. Prescription Issued</strong><br/>
If tretinoin is appropriate, prescription is sent to you electronically or printed. Take it to a pharmacy.</p><p><strong>4. Pick Up Tretinoin</strong><br/>
Common brands in India: Retino-A (0.025%, 0.05%, 0.1%), Tretin, A-Ret. (20g).</p><div class="article-fold" id="articleFold"><h2>What Concentration Should You Start With?</h2><p><strong>Rule: Start low, go slow.</strong></p><ul><li><strong>0.025% (Beginners, no prior retinoid use)</strong> Lowest, mildest irritation, slowest results, but safest. Most skin types can tolerate this well.</li><li><strong>0.05% (Experienced retinoid users or after 8 weeks at 0.025%)</strong> Moderate strength, faster results, more irritation.</li><li><strong>0.1% (Advanced users)</strong> Strongest, fastest results, most irritation. Only after proven tolerance at lower concentrations.</li></ul><p><strong>For Indian skin specifically</strong> Start 0.025%. Indian skin (South Asian, darker melanin content) has higher post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) risk. Low concentration minimizes irritation-triggered PIH. Slow escalation is safer.</p><p><strong>For sensitive skin or rosacea</strong> 0.025% is non-negotiable. Even consider starting 2 times weekly instead of nightly.</p><h2>How to Use Tretinoin: The Protocol</h2><p><strong>Cleanser → Dry skin → Pea-size amount of tretinoin → Moisturizer → Sunscreen (next AM)</strong></p><h3>1. Cleanse</h3><p>Gentle, non-stripping cleanser. CeraVe Hydrating Cleanser, La Roche-Posay Toleriane Purifying Foaming Cleanser, or India-specific: Cetaphil, Minimalist Face Cleanser. Avoid sodium lauryl sulfate (too harsh).</p><h3>2. Dry Your Skin Completely</h3><p>This is critical. Tretinoin penetrates damp skin more deeply, causing irritation. Dry for 10 minutes after cleansing.</p><h3>3. Apply Pea-Size Amount</h3><p>NOT a dime-size, a pea-size. Tretinoin is potent. Too much = severe irritation. Dab on forehead, cheeks, nose, chin. Gently massage in for 30 seconds. Wait 5 minutes before next step.</p><h3>4. Moisturize</h3><p>Essential. Tretinoin dries skin. Use a good moisturizer — Cetaphil, CeraVe, Moisturex, Minimalist Hyaluronic Acid + B5. This buffers irritation.</p><h3>5. Sunscreen (Next Morning)</h3><p>SPF 50+ every day. Non-negotiable. Tretinoin increases photosensitivity. UV exposure causes sunburn, permanent hyperpigmentation (especially risk in Indian skin), and photoaging. Daily sunscreen is anti-aging's foundation.</p><h3>Frequency</h3><p><strong>Week 1</strong> 2 times per week (e.g., Monday, Thursday)</p><p><strong>Week 3</strong> 3 times per week (e.g., Mon, Wed, Fri)</p><p><strong>Week 5+</strong> Every other night or nightly (as tolerated)</p><p>Slow titration lets your skin barrier adapt. Rushing causes excessive irritation and purging.</p><h2>Understanding Purging vs. Worsening</h2><p><strong>Purging</strong> Temporary increase in breakouts during first 4 weeks. Your skin speeds up cell turnover. Dead skin cells, sebum, and bacteria are pushed out faster. It looks worse before it gets better.</p><p><strong>Is purging normal?</strong> Yes, in 40% of users. Not everyone purges; some skip straight to improvement.</p><p><strong>How long does purging last?</strong> Typically 4 weeks. If breakouts persist beyond 12 weeks, it's not purging — consult your physician. You may need to lower concentration or frequency.</p><p><strong>Purging vs. Worsening</strong> If you have severe rash, extreme pain, or blistering, it's not purging — stop and contact your physician. Minor dryness, flaking, slight redness = normal. Intense burning, spreading rash = problem.</p><h2>PIH (Post-Inflammatory Hyperpigmentation) and Melanin-Rich Skin</h2><p>PIH is darkening of skin after inflammation (like acne, irritation, or tretinoin damage). It's more common and lasts longer in melanin-rich skin — Indian skin, Black skin, South Asian skin.</p><p><strong>Why tretinoin increases PIH risk</strong></p><ul><li>Tretinoin causes irritation during adaptation</li><li>Irritation triggers melanin production (skin tries to protect itself)</li><li>Result: dark spots, post-inflammatory discoloration</li></ul><p><strong>Prevention</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Start low (0.025%)</strong> Minimal irritation = minimal PIH risk</li><li><strong>Use strict sunscreen (SPF 50+)</strong> UV + tretinoin = darkening. Daily sun protection is essential.</li><li><strong>Avoid other irritants</strong> Don't use AHAs, BHAs, or. <a href="/vitamin-deficiency" style="color:var(--gold);text-decoration:underline;text-decoration-color:rgba(184,146,46,0.3);transition:all .2s">vitamin</a> C early on. Stick with tretinoin as your only active for the first 8 weeks.</li><li><strong>Avoid physical irritation</strong> No picking, excessive washing, or harsh towels.</li></ul><p><strong>If PIH develops</strong> Don't panic. It's usually temporary. Continue tretinoin + strict sun protection. PIH typically fades over 3 months. Azelaic acid (Finacea) can speed fading in dark-skinned individuals.</p><h2>Indian Tretinoin Brands and Costs</h2><p><strong>Common brands</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Retino-A (Johnson & Johnson)</strong> 0.025%, 0.05%, 0.1% cream. Most trusted..</li><li><strong>Tretin (Dr. Reddy's)</strong> 0.025%, 0.05% cream. Affordable..</li><li><strong>A-Ret (Jan Aushadhi)</strong> 0.025%, 0.05% cream. Govt. initiative, very cheap..</li><li><strong>Tretinoin (generic)</strong> Various manufacturers..</li></ul><p><strong>Quantity</strong> Most tubes are 20g. Lasts 2 months with nightly use (pea-size).</p><p><strong>Cost per month</strong> very affordable.</p><h2>What Not to Use With Tretinoin</h2><p><strong>Avoid during first 8 weeks</strong></p><ul><li><strong>AHAs (glycolic, lactic acid)</strong> Too much exfoliation. Barrier damage, irritation, PIH.</li><li><strong>BHAs (salicylic acid)</strong> Same issue.</li><li><strong>Vitamin C serums</strong> Can be oxidizing + irritating when combined with tretinoin. Wait 8+ weeks.</li><li><strong>Benzoyl peroxide</strong> Inactivates tretinoin. If you have acne and want benzoyl peroxide, use it separately (morning only).</li><li><strong>Multiple actives</strong> Stick with tretinoin. Let it be your main treatment.</li></ul><p><strong>Safe to use</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Niacinamide</strong> Soothing, reduces irritation. Good pairing.</li><li><strong>Hyaluronic acid</strong> Hydrating. Pairs well.</li><li><strong>Ceramides</strong> Barrier support. Excellent with tretinoin.</li></ul><div class="cta-card"><p><strong>Want tretinoin prescribed safely?</strong> Skin assessment + proper concentration + monitoring prevents PIH and purging disasters. <a href="#cta">Get a telehealth prescription with arq. →</a></p></div><h2>Timeline: When Will You See Results?</h2><p><strong>Acne</strong> Purging weeks 1 improvement weeks 8. By week 16, most people see 50% reduction in breakouts.</p><p><strong>Fine lines / Anti-aging</strong> Takes longer. Week 12 you may see subtle improvement. Significant results by 16 weeks.</p><p><strong>Texture / PIH</strong> Gradual improvement over months with consistent use and sun protection.</p><p><strong>Realistic expectations</strong> Tretinoin is powerful, but not overnight. 3 months of consistent use before judging results.</p><h2>arq.'s Approach: Tretinoin with Oversight</h2><ul><li><strong>Consultation</strong> 10-minute video, skin assessment, determine if tretinoin is right for you</li><li><strong>Concentration selection</strong> Based on skin type, Fitzpatrick scale, prior retinoid experience</li><li><strong>Prescription issued</strong> With detailed use instructions (frequency, moisturizer recs, sunscreen protocol)</li><li><strong>2-week check-in</strong> How's irritation? Signs of purging? Adjust frequency if needed.</li><li><strong>8-week follow-up</strong> Assess improvement. Any PIH? Adjust concentration if ready to escalate.</li><li><strong>Ongoing</strong> Quarterly check-ins if desired. We monitor and adjust — tretinoin isn't fire-and-forget.</li></ul><p>This is especially important for Indian skin. PIH risks are real. Proper supervision prevents it.</p></section><!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ --></div><!-- end article-fold --><div class="read-more-wrap" id="readMoreWrap"><button class="read-more-btn" id="readMoreBtn">
 Continue reading. <i class="ph-bold ph-caret-down"></i></button></div><section class="faq"><div class="faq-head"><span class="eyebrow" style="justify-content: center; display: flex;">Questions</span><h2>Frequently asked about Tretinoin</h2></div><ul class="faq-list"><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>Is tretinoin the same as retinol or retinoid?</summary><div class="faq-ans">No. Retinol is a weaker over-the-counter form found in many skincare products. Tretinoin (retinoic acid) is the strongest, prescription-only form. Your skin must convert retinol → retinaldehyde → retinoic acid (tretinoin). Tretinoin skips this conversion, working directly and fast. This is why tretinoin is more effective but also more irritating and requires medical supervision.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>What is 'purging' and how long does it last?</summary><div class="faq-ans">Purging is temporary worsening of acne during the first 4 weeks of tretinoin. Your skin speeds up cell turnover, pushing out comedones (blackheads/whiteheads) and congestion faster. This is not a sign to stop — it's a sign it's working. Purging typically lasts 4 weeks depending on skin type and concentration. If breakouts persist beyond 12 weeks, it may not be purging — consult your physician.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>Why is sun protection so critical on tretinoin?</summary><div class="faq-ans">Tretinoin increases cell turnover and makes skin thinner and more photosensitive. UV exposure + tretinoin = severe sunburn, permanent hyperpigmentation (especially in darker skin), and even photoaging. SPF 50+ sunscreen + physical sun avoidance is non-negotiable. Missing this step will undo tretinoin's benefits and cause lasting damage in melanin-rich skin.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>Can I use tretinoin with other actives like niacinamide or AHAs?</summary><div class="faq-ans">Avoid combining tretinoin with AHAs (glycolic acid, lactic acid) or BHAs (salicylic acid) early on — too much exfoliation causes irritation and barrier damage. Niacinamide is safe and actually helps reduce irritation. Vitamin C is safe. Avoid benzoyl peroxide (reduces tretinoin efficacy). As your skin adapts (8+ weeks), you can cautiously layer other products, but start minimal — let tretinoin be your main active.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>What is PIH and why does it happen in darker skin?</summary><div class="faq-ans">PIH (Post-Inflammatory Hyperpigmentation) is darkening of the skin after inflammation (like acne or irritation). It's more common and lasts longer in melanin-rich skin (brown, black, South Asian skin). Tretinoin's irritation during purging can trigger PIH if not managed carefully. Prevention: gentle tretinoin initiation, strict sun protection, and avoiding unnecessary irritants. If PIH develops, it usually fades over months with continued sun protection and tretinoin use.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>Can I use tretinoin during pregnancy?</summary><div class="faq-ans">No. Tretinoin is teratogenic — it can cause birth defects in the fetus. If you're pregnant or trying to conceive, tretinoin is contraindicated. Discuss alternatives with your physician (azelaic acid, niacinamide-based products, gentle skincare). If you become pregnant while on tretinoin, stop immediately and inform your OB-GYN.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>How do I know which tretinoin concentration to start with?</summary><div class="faq-ans">For beginners with no prior retinoid use: start with 0.025% (lowest concentration). This minimizes irritation and allows your skin barrier to adapt. After 8 weeks, if well-tolerated, you can increase to 0.05% or 0.1%. Experienced retinoid users can start 0.05%. Darker skin types should start conservative (0.025%) due to PIH risk. Never start high concentrations — slow and steady wins the race.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>What if I have sensitive skin or rosacea?</summary><div class="faq-ans">Tretinoin can be used in sensitive skin and rosacea, but requires careful management: start ultra-low (0.025% or even 0.01%), use 2 times weekly initially, moisturize heavily, avoid other actives. Azelaic acid (0.2% prescription or 10% OTC) is often better for rosacea as first-line. Discuss your rosacea/sensitivity with your physician — they may recommend gentler approaches or lower frequencies.</div></details></li><li class="faq-item"><details><summary>Do I need to use tretinoin forever?</summary><div class="faq-ans">Not forever, but it depends on your goal. For acne: once clear, you can maintain with lower frequency (1-2x weekly) or stop. Results will fade over months if discontinued. For anti-aging: tretinoin works best with long-term consistent use. Many people use it indefinitely (low frequency) for aging prevention. Your physician helps you decide based on your goals and tolerance.</div></details></li></ul></section><!-- ═══ MEDICAL DISCLAIMER ═══ --><section class="medical-disclaimer"><div class="disclaimer-box"><strong>Medical Disclaimer</strong> This article is for educational purposes only and does not constitute medical advice. Tretinoin is a prescription medication with potential side effects and contraindications. Skin reactions vary by individual. Consult a licensed dermatologist or physician before starting tretinoin. arq. is India's physician-led online clinic — our physicians assess your skin and issue prescriptions appropriately. This information reflects current dermatological practice as of 2026.
